Pours a clear golden body with a beautiful white frothy head. A maize-colored suspension of yeast clouds the beer as I pour the last few drops into my glass. This leaves a swirl of tan on the top of the head - I'm impressed already. Tiny bubbles continue to rise from the bottom of my glass, long after I start drinking. As I work my way through this one, the head retains amazingly well despite the massive amounts of lacing left in the glass.
The smell is a combination of the sour funky smell with apples. The chardonnay is also apparent, but not significant. It doesn't provide the most powerful aroma, but what is there is excellent. A bit funky and a bit of wet straw.
What a great beer... as the first drink hit the back of my mouth, the tart punched me in the top of the mouth. My glands puckered and I took a look at the reactions of my buddy and my wife. We all kind of looked at each other and back at our glasses before grabbing another swig. Amazing. The tart was not overpowering, but definitely a significant part of the beer. My mouth is actually watering as I'm typing this review (seriously). The beer itself is excellent but the lemon-like zest is phenomenal. It is clean, crisp, and surprisingly dry. The taste is there and then gone. I get a little bit of the oaked wine taste...along with some other flavors I'm not sure if I've even had before. This is just outstanding. I split this bottle with two others, but could have easily had one to myself and not gotten tired of it. How do we get this delivered to Indiana?
