4.2/5  rDev -4.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Batch 003
 This is a light, hazy blonde color with a massive, bubbly, beastie head with air-filled bubbles, crown at least 3" high, very sticky with amazing retention. looks light and fluffy.
 The scent upfront is tart, sour berries, musty, citric yeast, wet wheat and grass, sweet tarts, green apples, green veggies. Very natural and earthy smelling overall.
 The taste is also tart and sour upfront with a huge earthy yeastie flavor. There's citric fruits like lemmons along with crab apples, and other "wild" fruits like tiny, wild strawberries and raspberries. There's an earthy bitterness for balance...the wheat and dried hay-like flavor pops out at the end too. 
 The feel is a light, refreshing and slightly dry kick but the sticky foam gives it a soft feel on the way down. Very smooth actually.
 I really love these unique and experimental brews, pushing the boundries is what it's all about, especially when it works! 933 charactersGratefulBeerGuy, Jul 09, 2008
4.37/5  rDev -0.9%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5From a .375 bottle.
The beer pours an impressive, hazy gold color with impressive head retention and very good lacing. The nose on this beer is the best thing about it in my opinion, consisting of honey, citrus, white pepper, vanilla and some light sour funk. This beer smells very complex. However, considering the way this beer smells, I'm a bit surprised by the level of sour in this beer. There is a hint of honey and vanilla, but it's just about overwhelmed by the sour funk. As the beer sits in the glass the sour dies down a bit and blends in more with the other flavors. I get some more vanilla and even cherry now, which is interwoven with the sour funk. The beer is medium bodied, but there's a crispness in the finish that I really like, that helps to make this beer very refreshing and drinkable. 
Very interesting beer. Not entirely my cup of tea, but it was fun to try nonetheless. 897 charactersJohn_M, Jul 07, 2008
4.62/5  rDev +4.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Thanks goes out to prototypic for this gem.
A - Color is on the light side of gold. A small amount of cloudiness make it into the bottle but the color still remians bright. Head looked good topping out at just over an inch with a careful pour. A constant supply of rising carbonation sent the retention through the roof. The resulting lace left behind looks good as well.
S - Some funkiness shows up in the aroma and is not too strong. The wood is a nice compliment to the initial funk. Some fruit notes come in about midway - apple and grape. Notes of cinnamon and alcohol finish things up. The aroma was not as strong as expected but still very pleasing.
T - A sour and funky flavor from the Brett dominates. The funk fades quick to allow some fruitiness to play off the sour flavor. Starts to resemble young green apples. The oak adds a layer of flavor that is a great under pinning for the sour / bitter fruit. Alcohol is present throughout the flavor but is kept in check by the other robust flavors and complexity of the brew. Very nice.
M - Medium bodied with a high level of carbonation that works well for this brew. The oak feels like it adds to the body which is nice. Finish is sour and fruity and does not stop.
D - Drinkability is very good. The Brett is strong but does not overtake everything this beer is trying to showcase. The oak presence works wonders in this particular beer - adding flavor and body. The higher alcohol does place some limits on the amount that should be consumed in a session. Still, very good and glad I got the chance to try it. 1,575 characterscsmiley, Jul 05, 2008
